latestPosts.caption:
Never beg for a seat when you can build your own table. Read that twice✨

Eight months ago, I found myself interviewing for aesthetic sales jobs with 12 years of industry experience. You’d think that would make the process easier, right? But after multiple interviews, presentations, and working events to build connections, I was repeatedly rejected. Why? Because I didn’t have a college degree or there were concerns about my commitment after just having a baby.

It was a tough time. I felt discouraged and questioned my worth. I knew my capabilities—why couldn’t they see it? Then I had a realization: if these companies didn’t believe I could represent their brand, I would create my own. After all, I had already built a successful business from the ground up during a global pandemic. Surely, I could do it again—only better this time.

Fast forward to today, and here we are—8 months later with 4 locations, 4 more opening by the fall, operating in 6 states, and a team of over 40 amazing staff members at @sageheadspa 

The moral of this story is sometimes rejection is redirection.

latestPosts.caption:
Meet the Creators of @sageheadspa Emily & Desarai

Emily, a licensed esthetician with a background in medical aesthetics, is a seasoned entrepreneur—Sage HeadSpa is her third successful business. Desarai, a licensed master cosmetologist, brings over a decade of beauty industry experience and hands-on expertise.

The two have known each other for nearly 15 years and launched Sage HeadSpa almost two years ago. Together, they developed the signature Sage HeadSpa Protocol—a transformative client experience built after months of experimenting with the right tools, techniques, products, and equipment.

Since then, they’ve opened 8 thriving HeadSpa locations across the Southeast and continue to grow.

As demand for HeadSpa services grew, they noticed a gap in the industry—there was no clear guide on how to start, build, and scale a HeadSpa business. In response, Emily created a business course focused on helping beauty professionals bring their own vision to life. The HeadSpa Blueprint walks students through every stage of launching a HeadSpa, including:
	•	Getting your idea down on paper
	•	Choosing the right services to offer
	•	Building a physical space
	•	Creating a standout brand
	•	Finding and retaining clients
	•	Leading a team and managing day-to-day operations
	•	Understanding business finances
	•	Planning for long-term growth and success
	•	Staying grounded and stress-free as a business owner

Their mission is to bridge the gap in this market and make the HeadSpa experience a lasting staple in the U.S. beauty and wellness industry.

Due to high demand, they also added technique training—offered online for foundational skills, and in-person for in-depth, hands-on training in their proprietary Sage HeadSpa Protocol. This allows students to not only learn the business side, but also master the art of touch and deliver a true HeadSpa experience.

latestPosts.caption:
When You’re the Blueprint, the Copies Are Inevitable

Being copied is frustrating—let’s be real. Watching someone replicate your branding, services, captions, or even your exact words can feel like a punch to the gut, especially when you’ve poured your heart into building something original.

But then it hits you: they’re always one step behind.

If someone’s copying everything you do, congratulations—you’ve officially become their strategy. And that’s not arrogance, that’s reality. You’re the one creating the roadmap. They’re just following it.

But here’s the difference:
Trendsetters get copied. Leaders get followed.
Originals? They keep evolving.

They can duplicate your menu, mimic your tone, and even try to emulate your experience—but what they’ll never have is your why. Your vision. Your instinct. Your pulse on what’s next.

The real threat isn’t being copied—it’s getting so caught up in the noise that you slow down. But when you stay focused and keep pushing forward, they’ll always be chasing what you already did yesterday.

So to those observing and drawing inspiration from our work — we see it, and we get it. But while you’re looking back, we’re already looking ahead. We’re focused on growth, evolution, and staying aligned with our purpose. Because that’s what keeps us original — and always just out of reach.

latestPosts.caption:
Wow—what a year 33 has been. As my birthday approaches tomorrow, I’ve been doing a lot of reflecting. 

So many highs and lows. I started the year feeling like I was on top of the world. We had four Sage HeadSpa locations open and thriving, with three more on the way. I had a long list of personal, business, financial, and family goals—and I was on track to hit them. My #1 business goal? Hit 100k followers on Instagram.

Then, in mid-June, everything changed. Our Instagram was hacked, and in an instant, it felt like everything we’d worked so hard to build was slipping through my fingers. I had two choices: give up and let it all fall apart—or fight like hell to save it.

I chose to fight.
But I won’t lie—the stress nearly broke me. All I could think about was my team. The incredible women at Sage who show up every day with heart and purpose—I couldn’t let them down. Thankfully, after a long, exhausting process, we got our page back.

Then in September, just when I thought things might calm down, sewage backed up into our home. It felt like life kept testing me—personally, professionally, emotionally. I was drained.

By January, I knew something had to change. I couldn’t carry the same heaviness and fear into another year. I had to reset my mindset and how I speak to myself. I had to let go of comparison and start honoring how far I’ve come.

Through it all, God has continued to bless me—especially with another healthy baby arriving soon. I’m beyond grateful. My kids bring me endless love, joy, and purpose.

This year has tested me, broken me, and rebuilt me. It’s shown me that building a business isn’t just about strategy or having the best ideas. It’s about holding the most weight—and still executing.

It’s about standing in the middle of the storm with no map, no lifeline, and no guarantee it’ll work—yet choosing not to flinch. Progress doesn’t come from comfort; it comes from pressure. From discipline. From doing the right thing, even when everything feels like it’s falling apart.

And that’s exactly what I intend to keep doing—building, growing, and showing up with heart and grit. I can’t wait to see what’s ahead. Cheers to 34

latestPosts.caption:
Photo captured mid photoshoot putting out a fire😩

Being a business owner is the toughest, yet most rewarding, role I’ve ever taken on.

I started in esthetics back in 2011, working in plastic surgery, med spas, and dermatology offices. Even then, I would daydream about creating a space where estheticians didn’t just work — they thrived. A place free from the physical and mental stress that’s so common in our industry.

Working hands-on with people is an energy exchange. At Sage, I truly believe clients can unwind and relax because our team is grounded, cared for, and genuinely at peace.

What I’ve learned over these past two years is how important it is to protect your own energy and peace. I’ve brought my dream to life — but there’s an entire other side of business ownership that rarely gets talked about. The dark side. The hard side.

It’s not always rainbows and butterflies. And sometimes, clients, staff, friends, and even family don’t fully see what we carry behind the scenes.

But here’s what I know to be true: founders, creators, builders — we’re built different. You can knock us down, but we don’t stay down. We pivot, we rise, and we figure it out — every single time.
